  <static seed="1444" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations4.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{-t-5}{t+9}} = {-\frac{t}{t+6}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-15\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{\left(t+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+6\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{-t-5}{t+9}} \amp = {-\frac{t}{t+6}} \\
   {\frac{-t-5}{t+9}} \cdot {\left(t+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+6\right)} \amp = {-\frac{t}{t+6}} \cdot {\left(t+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+6\right)} \\
   {\left(-t-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+6\right)} \amp = {-t\mathopen{}\left(t+9\right)} \\
   {-t^{2}-6t-5t-30} \amp = {-t^{2}-9t} \\
   -2t \amp = 30 \\
   t \amp = -15
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{\left(t+9\right)\mathopen{}\left(t+6\right)} \ne 0</m>, which is equivalent to <m>t \ne -9</m> and <m>t \ne -6</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>t = -15</m>.</p>
</solution>
